"Zhang Y., Wang H., Sun J., Drange H.","Changes in the tropical cyclone genesis potential index over the western north pacific in the SRES A2 Scenario",2010,"Advances in Atmospheric Sciences","27","6",,"1246","1258",,,10.1007/s00376-010-9096-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-78649478542&partnerID=40&md5=0730a427626ce2d10aa067b69c2ddaf5","Nansen-Zhu International Research Centre, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Climate Change Research Center, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Department of Geophysics, University of Bergen, Allégaten 70, 5007 Bergen, Norway; Graduate University of Chinese Academy of Science, Beijing 100049, China","Zhang, Y., Nansen-Zhu International Research Centre, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Climate Change Research Center, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Graduate University of Chinese Academy of Science, Beijing 100049, China; Wang, H., Nansen-Zhu International Research Centre, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Climate Change Research Center, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Sun, J., Nansen-Zhu International Research Centre, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Climate Change Research Center, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Drange, H., Nansen-Zhu International Research Centre, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Department of Geophysics, University of Bergen, Allégaten 70, 5007 Bergen, Norway","The Tropical Cyclone Genesis Potential Index (GPI) was employed to investigate possible impacts of global warming on tropical cyclone genesis over the western North Pacific (WNP). The outputs of 20th century climate simulation by eighteen GCMs were used to evaluate the models' ability to reproduce tropical cyclone genesis via the GPI. The GCMs were found in general to reasonably reproduce the observed spatial distribution of genesis. Some of the models also showed ability in capturing observed temporal variation. Based on the evaluation, the models (CGCM3. 1-T47 and IPSL-CM4) found to perform best when reproducing both spatial and temporal features were chosen to project future GPI. Results show that both of these models project an upward trend of the GPI under the SRES A2 scenario, however the rate of increase differs between them. © 2010 Chinese National Committee for International Association of Meteorology and Atmospheric Sciences, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Science Press and Springer-Verlag Berlin Heidelberg.","Genesis Potential Index; global warming; SRES A2; tropical cyclone; western North Pacific",,,,,,,"Bengtsson, L., Botzet, M., Esch, M., Hurricanetype vortices in a general-circulation model (1995) Tellus (A), 47 (2), pp. 175-196; Bengtsson, L., Hodges, K.I., Esch, M., Keenlyside, N., Luo, J.J., Yamagata, T., How may tropical cyclones change in a warmer climate? (2007) Tellus (A), 59 (4), pp. 539-561; Bister, M., Emanuel, K., Dissipative heating and hurricane intensity (1998) Meteor. Atmos. Phys., 52, pp. 233-240; Bleck, R., Rooth, C., Hu, D., Smith, L.T., Salinity-driven thermocline transients in a wind- and thermohaline-forced isopycnic coordinate model of the North Atlantic (1992) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 22, pp. 1486-1505; Camargo, S.J., Zebiak, S.E., Improving the detection and tracking of tropical cyclones in atmospheric general circulation models (2002) Wea. Forecasting, 17 (6), pp. 1152-1162; Camargo, S.J., Emanuel, K.A., Sobel, A.H., Use of a genesis potential index to diagnose ENSO effects on tropical cyclone genesis (2007) J. Climate, 20 (19), pp. 4819-4834; Camargo, S.J., Sobel, A.H., Barnston, A.G., Emanuel, K.A., Tropical cyclone genesis potential index in climate models (2007) Tellus(A), 59 (4), pp. 428-443; Caron, L.P., Jones, C.G., Analy